Dialogue: 0,0:12:52.21,0:13:04.86,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\blur1\bord0\fade(800,0)\c&HDBD9E1&\3c&HA9A278&\pos(640,1008)}Tinian
Dialogue: 1,0:12:53.98,0:12:59.07,Default,,0,0,0,,The US Army seized Saipan, Guam, Tinian, and the rest of Mariana Island Chain
Dialogue: 1,0:12:59.07,0:13:02.44,Default,,0,0,0,,to use them as a springboard \Nfor air raids on Japan proper.
Dialogue: 1,0:13:02.44,0:13:06.07,Default,,0,0,0,,The next step would be capturing Iwo Jima, \Noffering a base right on the way. {meaning if you draw a direct line from mariana to tokyo, it lies on that line, I feel like there should be some precise english word for it but I can't recall it}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:06.07,0:13:08.85,Default,,0,0,0,,The course of their intentions has been made clear.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:09.74,0:13:13.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Aiming to bolster the defense of Iwo Jima, \Nthe Army high command
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.71,0:13:19.88,Default,,0,0,0,,dispatched to the island a tank unit under \NMajor Nishi Takeichi, the Olympic gold medalist equestrian.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:20.42,0:13:23.82,Default,,0,0,0,,A famous pilot, Rear Admiral Ichimaru Toshinosuke,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:23.82,0:13:28.59,Default,,0,0,0,,along with marines and a construction battalion of the 27th Air Squadron under his command,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:28.59,0:13:30.77,Default,,0,0,0,,also disembarked on the island.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:31.56,0:13:37.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Consequently, the defenders of the measly 20 square kilometers that is Iwo Jima,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:37.15,0:13:41.44,Default,,0,0,0,,mainly - Kuribayashi's 109th Division,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:41.44,0:13:48.98,Default,,0,0,0,,numbered 15,500 Army personnel \Nand 7,000 Navy personnel.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.93,0:13:57.32,Default,,0,0,0,,After the reinforcements had finally been stationed, \Nsenior officers held a strategy meeting.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:00.17,0:14:05.17,Default,,0,0,0,,As a division commander, \NI couldn't be happier to have your support.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:05.17,0:14:07.97,Default,,0,0,0,,That's because I still need several official approvals,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:08.63,0:14:10.85,Default,,0,0,0,,authorizing me to defend this island to the last. {no clue why he needs approval for that, seems like a no brainer for the japanese at the time, those guys don't look much like officials either, but it clearly is shokan so idk; そこでこの島の死守にあたり諸官の御賛同を得たい}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:10.85,0:14:17.59,Default,,0,0,0,,As you have already seen, this island is indeed devoid of any natural fortress features that favor the defender. {this various official again, I guess they kinda are after all}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.59,0:14:19.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Only the flat open terrain.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:19.89,0:14:23.07,Default,,0,0,0,,That's why I built a fortress of our own, underground.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:23.07,0:14:28.93,Default,,0,0,0,,And my goal is to defend this place \Nfor as long as I can, until the very last man.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:28.93,0:14:33.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Indeed, I was deeply impressed \Nby the terrific fortifications you've erected.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:33.12,0:14:35.93,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what kind of strategy would you employ \Nwhen the enemy attacks?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.93,0:14:38.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Before, our army's conventional wisdom dictated
Dialogue: 0,0:14:38.85,0:14:43.14,Default,,0,0,0,,that in the case of island defense, \Na beachfront tactic is to be adopted,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:43.14,0:14:47.97,Default,,0,0,0,,where we deploy our line artillery on the shore \Nand use it to shell any fleet that approaches.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.03,0:14:50.45,Default,,0,0,0,,I plan to deviate from that.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:50.84,0:14:52.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Why is that?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.45,0:14:56.90,Default,,0,0,0,,The artillery at our disposal only includes 12 320-mm guns,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:56.90,0:15:02.46,Default,,0,0,0,,22 150-mm guns, \Nand some other guns less than 15 cm in caliber. {added dash here though we usually don't do it because otherwise kinda hard to read, as if they have one gun that's 12320mm}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:02.46,0:15:06.32,Default,,0,0,0,,With these, you can't hope to seriously damage any warship, let alone sink it.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:06.32,0:15:13.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Therefore, our plan is to let them land, lure them to the center of the island, and squash them there.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:13.63,0:15:15.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Very well. I support it.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:15.97,0:15:16.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:16.72,0:15:19.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Which brings me to one more favor I'd like to ask for.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.43,0:15:21.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Whatever happens, don't order a banzai charge.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:21.98,0:15:24.65,Default,,0,0,0,,If I may, what do you mean by that?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:24.65,0:15:29.66,Default,,0,0,0,,No matter how few soldiers you have left, \Nkeep manning your positions and don't attack.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:30.76,0:15:36.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Lately, we've been encouraged to order a desperate charge \Nwith a "banzai" shout when the end is near.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:36.41,0:15:40.12,Default,,0,0,0,,However, this tactic only hastens the ultimate defeat.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:40.12,0:15:45.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Our mission is to protect the island for as long as we can, \Nbe it even for a day or half a day more.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.44,0:15:46.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Please keep this in mind.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.72,0:15:52.91,Default,,0,0,0,,The final decision will only be passed down by me.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.91,0:15:58.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Until then, defend your positions \Nand fight with a goal of attaining a 10:1 casualty rate. {/so hard that every our soldier kills at lest 10 of theirs}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:58.72,0:16:00.52,Default,,0,0,0,,I shall follow your orders to the letter.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.52,0:16:05.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, the focus shifted from defeating the enemy \Nto defending the island for as long as possible.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:05.33,0:16:10.10,Default,,0,0,0,,This strategy was a result of careful deliberation \Non how to delay the decisive battle for the mainland.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:10.10,0:16:14.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Kuribayashi may have also entertained \Nthe idea of leading a suicide charge
Dialogue: 0,0:16:14.22,0:16:17.68,Default,,0,0,0,,while chanting "banzai," \Nscattering their lives like cherry blossoms. {from episode 17}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.68,0:16:21.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Perhaps, he was also once determined \Nto go down in the most honorable fashion. {gracious (defeat, apology, etc.); graceful; honourable (e.g. death); noble; gallant; brave; manly; sportsmanlike}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:22.54,0:16:26.99,Default,,0,0,0,,However, he made a decision \Nto leave honor behind.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:26.99,0:16:33.89,Default,,0,0,0,,On February 19th, 1945, \Nmorning came to Iwo Jima.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:34.56,0:16:40.95,Default,,0,0,0,,On the ocean surface, glittering in the morning sun, \Nthe 3rd, 4th, and 5th US Marines divisions,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.45,0:16:46.94,Default,,0,0,0,,the landing party of 75,144 men total \Ncongregated in an enormous formation.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:48.00,0:16:54.45,Default,,0,0,0,,The landing support force under Rear Admiral Mitscher \Nincluded 17 fleet carriers
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.45,0:16:57.03,Default,,0,0,0,,and numbered 495 ships total.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:57.03,0:17:02.48,Default,,0,0,0,,The number of amphibious support personnel \Nclimbed all the way up to 111,300.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:07.19,0:17:11.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Secretary of the Navy Forrestal \Nwas also closely involved with the operation. {lit: especially participated in warships}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:11.51,0:17:15.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Their plan was to forcefully overrun the area in one fell swoop.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:16.08,0:17:21.83,Default,,0,0,0,,After we've expended so many shells in these last 3 days, \Nit's no wonder the Japanese took flight. {probably 秘めを上げた but i don't quite understand it}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:21.83,0:17:25.50,Default,,0,0,0,,No, they've not gone anywhere. \NThey are just lurking in a cave somewhere.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:30.00,0:17:33.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Over the course of 3 days leading up to this day,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.42,0:17:37.68,Default,,0,0,0,,the 20 square kilometers of Iwo Jima \Nhave been subjected to the heaviest bombardment yet.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:38.22,0:17:43.52,Default,,0,0,0,,120 tons of bombs. 2,254 rocket shells.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:43.52,0:17:46.71,Default,,0,0,0,,100 napalm shells also rained from the sky.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.32,0:17:55.44,Default,,0,0,0,,The 5th Fleet showered the island in 38,550 rounds, \Nfired from guns ranging from 16 inches to 5 inches.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:55.81,0:18:03.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Once the bombardment was concluded, the first wave \Nof 500 landing craft with 15,000 marines went ashore.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.66,0:18:49.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Start the attack!
Dialogue: 0,0:19:35.65,0:19:37.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Commanded by Lieutenant General Kuribayashi,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:37.63,0:19:39.67,Default,,0,0,0,,the operation has achieved its desired effect.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:39.67,0:19:44.07,Default,,0,0,0,,The death toll for the American side \Nwas 2,420 men already.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:44.07,0:19:49.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Other losses included 35 tanks and other armored vehicles, \Nas well as 100 landing craft.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:49.93,0:19:57.48,Default,,0,0,0,,By evening, over 30,000 men of the US Army \Nlanded on the island, along with their materiel. {not sure what to make of "talking about the material resources" and which sentence it belongs to; 戦車走行車35台上陸用集定100席を撃破したが 物量に物を言わせて夕方までにアメリカ軍3万人以上が上陸したのである}
Dialogue: 1,0:20:10.29,0:20:20.91,Default,,0,0,0,,The US landing party advanced on Mt. Suribachi first, then Chidori Airfield, Cliffs of Byoubu, and Motoyama Airfield.
Comment: 0,0:20:10.27,0:20:19.30,Sign,,0,0,0,,{too much movement, ignore}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:45.84,0:20:51.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Lieutenant General Kuribayashi's strategy \Nof using the caves for uncontested movement
Dialogue: 0,0:20:51.14,0:20:56.03,Default,,0,0,0,,produced the expected effect, \Nstopping the US Marines in their tracks. {/hindering the advance ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:10.43,0:21:12.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, on the 23rd,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:13.10,0:21:15.19,Default,,0,0,0,,after a day and night of brutal fighting,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:15.54,0:21:21.56,Default,,0,0,0,,at last, the marines raised a flag atop Mt. Suribachi, \Nthe highest peak of Iwo Jima. {actually "... fell/surrendered"}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:21.56,0:21:26.84,Default,,0,0,0,,All the Japanese troops, opposing them \Ndied in a banzai charge. {/were scattered/died before surrendering}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:26.84,0:21:29.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Mt. Suribachi has fallen. \NWay to go, boys!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:30.18,0:21:32.81,Default,,0,0,0,,In just a few more kilometers, \Nthe rest of the island will fall.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:33.66,0:21:40.43,Default,,0,0,0,,However, it took them 23 days \Nto cover said few more kilometers.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:48.29,0:21:53.14,Song,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:53.14,0:21:58.31,Song,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:54.84,0:21:59.31,Default,,0,0,0,,The signs of fatigue finally set in \Namong the Japanese troops,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:58.31,0:22:02.86,Song,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:59.31,0:22:02.86,Default,,0,0,0,,who had used up all of their \Nwater, provisions, and ammunition.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:03.16,0:22:07.91,Song,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:03.16,0:22:08.85,Default,,0,0,0,,It was around this time, when the encouragement from the mainland had arrived in the form of a radio broadcast.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:07.91,0:22:12.17,Song,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:12.17,0:22:16.91,Song,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.21,0:22:16.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Still,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.91,0:22:21.88,Song,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:17.41,0:22:21.86,Default,,0,0,0,,how many were there left \Nable to answer this call? {/respond to this encouragement}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:21.88,0:22:26.88,Song,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:24.09,0:22:28.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Before long, the caves in the north \Nbecame the only remaining holdout.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:28.05,0:22:33.15,Default,,0,0,0,,So Lieutenant General Kuribayashi \Ntelegraphed his farewell to Tokyo.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:39.37,0:22:43.88,Default,,0,0,0,,"The war has reached the final stages. {https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E6%A0%97%E6%9E%97%E5%BF%A0%E9%81%93#%E8%A8%A3%E5%88%A5%E3%81%AE%E9%9B%BB%E6%96%87 / taking the translation from the "Picture Letters _ from the Commander in Chief - Kuribayashi, Tadamichi, 1890 or 1-1945"}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:43.88,0:22:47.03,Default,,0,0,0,,All bullets have been fired, not a drop of water is left.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:47.03,0:22:52.95,Default,,0,0,0,,As we prepare to stage the final battle, \Nto all those remaining in the fight, {meaning those not on iwo}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:52.95,0:22:56.45,Default,,0,0,0,,I hereby bid my eternal farewell."
Dialogue: 0,0:23:02.44,0:23:07.80,Default,,0,0,0,,"All units will attack at midnight on the 17th, \Nfighting to the last man."
Dialogue: 0,0:23:07.80,0:23:12.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Thinking it dishonorable for him to return home, \Nhe issued an attack order, {lit: not forgiving himself being seen return ; was "Without care for his own personal safety" in HA}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:12.51,0:23:15.47,Default,,0,0,0,,fighting at the front line until the very end.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:15.47,0:23:17.31,Default,,0,0,0,,On the morning of 27th,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:17.31,0:23:24.26,Default,,0,0,0,,joined by his Chief of Staff Takaishi and Staff Officer Nakane, he used a pistol to finish off his injured body. {legend goes he asked either of them to kill him then commit suicide himself}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.28,0:23:28.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Even knowing they would ultimately fall,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:28.53,0:23:33.70,Default,,0,0,0,,he kept morale high and casualties low \Nby expressly forbidding any banzai charges.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:33.70,0:23:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The Lieutenant General's decision to take personal command and keep fighting to the bitter end {lit: stand personally in the fight}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:40.00,0:23:46.78,Default,,0,0,0,,resulted in the American losses exceeding \Nthose of the Japanese Army for the first time in the war.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:47.76,0:23:55.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Accordingly, that decision and his commander's attitude \Nare still highly regarded even to this day.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:57.79,0:24:07.47,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(100,0)}The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace.\NBut also instilled numerous lessons on how to live.{太平洋戦争はわれわれに平和の尊さを教えたがまた生きるための教訓を数多くのこしている}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.08,0:24:15.23,Default,,0,0,0,,On April 1, 1945, American troops began landing on Okinawa.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:15.23,0:24:19.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Fed up with the Okinawa garrison commander Lieutenant General Ushijima's self-sufficient approach,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.90,0:24:25.64,Default,,0,0,0,,the Combined Fleet Headquarters dispatch Yamato, \Nalong with her 2nd Fleet to assist them.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:26.17,0:24:32.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Thus, the world's biggest super-battleship Yamato \Nset out on a one-way trip to Okinawa.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.42,0:24:38.15,Sign,,0,0,0,,Episode 24 \NThe End of the Combined Fleet
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.15,0:24:36.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't miss the next decision: \NThe End of the Combined Fleet.
Comment: 0,0:24:43.11,0:24:43.15,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.52,0:24:48.42,Default,,0,0,50,,If you're a man, let's put your strength to test{男だったら　力を試せ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.42,0:24:52.37,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, keep your hopes sizzling{男だったら　希望(のぞみ)を燃やせ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:52.37,0:24:56.59,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, don't lose your heart{男だったら　くじけるな}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:56.59,0:25:05.21,Default,,0,0,50,,Because there's just you and me, a man and a man{俺もおまえも　男と男}
Dialogue: 0,0:25:05.21,0:25:13.59,Default,,0,0,50,,With crimson blood flowing in our veins all the same{おなじ真赤な　血が通う}
